# retry-explained.tflw — SPEC §4.4: `retry N` re-runs the whole test up to N more times on
# failure; a pass-after-retry is flagged **flaky**, never silently green. `random` values replay
# identically on every attempt (so a retried attempt can reuse the same key/namespace); `unique`
# values do not (their run-wide counter keeps advancing, so a retry never collides with data an
# earlier attempt already created). See retry-and-flake.tflw for the same idea against a real
# flaky endpoint with richer assertions.

@examples @retry
test "retry 2 re-runs a failing test up to twice more, reusing the same `random` key each time" retry 2
  # A fresh `random string 8` per attempt would defeat the whole point — the flaky-widget's
  # per-key attempt counter needs the SAME key across retries to actually recover.
  let key = random string 8
  api POST /flaky-widget body { key: {key} }
  # Attempt 1 gets 503, attempt 2 (first retry) gets 429, attempt 3 (second retry) gets 201 —
  # this test is reported `flaky` (passed, but only after retrying), which is the point.
  expect status equals 201

# M29: `retry honoring "Retry-After" up to N` (SPEC §5.1, decision 102b) is a per-`api`-step
# clause, not `test ... retry N` above — it re-sends *that one request* after sleeping the
# duration a real 429 response's `Retry-After` header names, instead of re-running the whole test
# from scratch. See tests/contract-and-retry.tflw for the fuller two-format (seconds/HTTP-date)
# proof against the same /retry-demo fixture; tests/.demo-fail/retry-after-not-honored.tflw shows
# the same endpoint failing without this clause — the gap it closes, made concrete.
@examples @retry
test "retry honoring \"Retry-After\" resends one request, not the whole test"
  api POST /retry-demo body { key: random string 8, format: "seconds" }
    retry honoring "Retry-After" up to 2
  expect status equals 200
